               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240916-89-person782">
                  WILLIAM 
                  TAIT
               <interp inst="t18240916-89-person782" type="surname" value="TAIT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-89-person782" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-89-person782" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a labourer under Mr. Hobson - I know all his hay forks; these three forks are my master's and here is the iron they are branded with.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240916-89-person783">
                  JOHN 
                  WEBB
               <interp inst="t18240916-89-person783" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-89-person783" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240916-89-person783" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a patrol. On the 20th of July, about half-past three o'clock in the morning, I was near Stamford-hill-gate; I saw the prisoner at a distance from me with something on his back - he was coming towards town from Mr. Hobson's, who lives near Stamford-hill gate; I and my partner followed and overtook him just by the Coach and Castle public-house, at Kingsland; he said he was going with the forks to the other farm, but he would not tell me where he got them; he then said he was going to Mr. William Rhodes's; and then that three of them belonged to his brother and one to himself.</p>

               <p>
            
